<p>3. The general statements set out in their â€˜outline of general policyâ€™ do not present any special difficulty, though the outline is not exhaustive, for example, it omits to mention that an important part of our policy is not only A2<a href="#f4">4</a> but also not to reward aggression.</p>

<p>4. The U.K.â€™s memo has to be seen of course against the background of present events includingâ€”</p>

<p>(a) The Peopleâ€™s Governmentâ€™s objective appears to be to drive U.N. forces out of Korea by force. What she proposes to do then in Korea is not disclosed.</p>

<p>(b) Its minimum conditions for settlement of Korea, where it is now engaged in aggression areâ€”</p>

<p>(i) Withdrawal of all U.N. forces from Korea.</p>

<p>(ii) Admission of Peopleâ€™s Government to United Nations as the proper representative of China.</p>

<p>(iii) Cession of Formosa to China.</p>

<p>These conditions leave unanswered the question what is to become of the U.N. objective viz. a free unified and independent Korea.</p>

<p>(c) The United States is not prepared to submit to the Peopleâ€™s Governmentâ€™s demands. Present U.S. administration is under great political pressure not to do so which will be increased by the recent speech by Senator Taft<a href="#f5">5</a> which you will have seen indicating the general view of the Republican Party. She is more likely to contemplate getting her forces out of Korea than of surrendering to what she consider to be the demands of Communist aggression in Korea.</p>

<p>5. As to the Peopleâ€™s Governmentâ€™s conditions (ii) and (iii) in (b) supra we do not think we can usefully either add to or modify the views expressed in Spenderâ€™s 4. The proposal to accept the Cairo Declaration â€˜in principleâ€™, the precise meaning of which is not clear to us, does not meet the observation on Formosa made in 4.</p>

